For people who are using Typescript, make an augmentation file and add this:
```
declare module "exceljs" {
  interface WorksheetModel {
    merges: object;
  }
}
```

I took the _merges from the original worksheet 
And performed the merge on the destination worksheet.
The layout of border will collapse, 
but if you devise it on the template file side, you can do it somehow

```
const copyWorkSheet = (workbook:ExcelJS.Workbook,srcSheetName:string,newSheetName:string) => {
  const srcSheet = workbook.getWorksheet(srcSheetName);
  let cloneSheet = workbook.addWorksheet('Sheet');
  cloneSheet.model = srcSheet.model
  _.each(srcSheet._merges,merge=>{
    cloneSheet.mergeCells(merge.top,merge.left,merge.bottom,merge.right)
  })
  cloneSheet.name = newSheetName
}
```

I had the same problem but others answers didn't worked well for me. 
Copying array from source to target does not work, I had to call the mergeCells() function for each merged cells instead.

**Hereafter my solution which seems OK with exceljs 4.4.0 :**

```ts 
public duplicateWorksheet(workbook: ExcelJS.Workbook, workSheetIndexOrName: number | string, name: string): ExcelJS.Worksheet {
    const sheetToClone = workbook.getWorksheet(workSheetIndexOrName);
    const cloneSheet = workbook.addWorksheet("Sheet");
    cloneSheet.model = { ...sheetToClone.model };
    cloneSheet.name = name;
    sheetToClone.model.merges.forEach(merge => cloneSheet.mergeCells(merge));

    return cloneSheet;
  }
```
